09:40.400 --> 09:42.710
- Oliver.
- Ah, Mr. Delfont.

09:42.880 --> 09:44.234
- Stanley.
- Well, hello there.

09:44.400 --> 09:45.356
- Welcome to England.
- Thank you.

09:45.560 --> 09:47.710
Welcome to Newcastle.
Wonderful to see you.

09:47.880 --> 09:48.711
How was your journey?

09:48.880 --> 09:50.109
Well, you know, that train trip

09:50.280 --> 09:51.634
sure takes it out of you, doesn't it?

09:51.800 --> 09:53.120
Mm-hm.
- Good, good, good, good, good.

09:53.320 --> 09:55.436
Uh, we're delighted
you've taken the trouble

09:55.600 --> 09:57.034
to come and greet us, Mr. Delfont.

09:57.240 --> 09:58.639
Please, call me Bernie.

09:58.800 --> 10:00.632
I want to do everything
I possibly can to make sure

10:00.800 --> 10:02.359
that this tour gets off on the right foot.

10:02.520 --> 10:04.272
Yes, well, that's something
we were hoping to discuss

10:04.440 --> 10:05.839
with you over dinner, actually.

10:06.040 --> 10:08.031
We're a little concerned
that some of the tour dates

10:08.200 --> 10:10.157
are going to be in conflict
with the shooting dates

10:10.320 --> 10:11.674
of this Robin Hood picture we're doing.

10:11.880 --> 10:13.837
I would love to have dinner with you.

10:14.000 --> 10:16.958
Unfortunately,
due at the theater in ten minutes.

10:17.120 --> 10:18.474
- Ah.
- One of my other acts.

10:18.680 --> 10:19.795
Norman Wisdom.

10:21.040 --> 10:22.633
Bright young talent. Blazing.

10:22.800 --> 10:25.440
And we must nurture
the young generation, gentlemen.

10:25.640 --> 10:27.199
I know you both feel as passionately

10:27.360 --> 10:28.589
about that as I do.

10:28.760 --> 10:31.229
- Hmm.
- Anyway, get yourselves settled in.

10:31.440 --> 10:33.113
Charming staff. Charming.

10:33.280 --> 10:34.475
We shall speak anon.

10:34.640 --> 10:35.835
- All righty.
- All right.

10:36.000 --> 10:37.877
- Enjoy the show.
- I shall.

10:42.280 --> 10:45.671
Stan, he does know
we're making a movie, right,

10:45.840 --> 10:47.877
and we're doing this tour
while we're waiting

10:48.080 --> 10:49.434
for things to come together?

10:49.600 --> 10:51.830
Yeah, it's all been spelled out, you know.

10:52.040 --> 10:54.509
All been agreed up front, 110%.

10:54.680 --> 10:55.670
Good.

10:57.160 --> 10:58.230
Where'd you get that?

10:58.400 --> 11:01.438
Uh, it's a... I got it in a shop.

11:01.600 --> 11:03.432
Like a beret, you can fold it up

11:03.640 --> 11:06.598
and stick it in your pocket like that.

11:08.200 --> 11:09.520
Well, here we are.

11:11.560 --> 11:14.234
Well, we'll only be here one night.

11:15.000 --> 11:16.149
Well, three.

11:17.720 --> 11:18.755
Right.

11:25.440 --> 11:29.195
Come on, Stan. Let's get out of the rain.

11:31.680 --> 11:33.159
Good evening, sir.

12:10.400 --> 12:13.392
Now, can't you see
she's standing right there?

12:13.560 --> 12:16.473
You don't need to ring that bell.

12:31.840 --> 12:32.989
Good eve...

12:34.320 --> 12:35.594
That wasn't me.

12:40.320 --> 12:41.879
Please pardon my friend.

12:42.040 --> 12:44.873
You just wait till I tell me mam it's you.

12:45.040 --> 12:47.714
We never get anybody famous
staying here.

12:47.880 --> 12:51.191
To be honest, I thought you'd retired.

12:52.400 --> 12:53.674
- No.No.

12:53.840 --> 12:55.353
No, we're-we're...

12:55.520 --> 12:57.397
we're getting older,
but we're not done yet.

12:59.080 --> 13:00.309
Where are youse
gonna be appearing, then?

13:00.480 --> 13:01.470
The Theatre Royal?

13:02.680 --> 13:03.829
No, it's, uh...

13:04.000 --> 13:05.877
No, it's the Queen's Hall.

13:06.040 --> 13:08.873
Queen's Hall? That can't be right.

13:09.040 --> 13:10.951
All the big stars perform
at the Theatre Royal.

13:11.120 --> 13:12.155
That's where you'll be playing.

13:12.320 --> 13:13.594
Well, I'm sure you're right.

13:13.760 --> 13:14.716
Is it Theatre Royal?

13:14.880 --> 13:16.154
No, it's just the Queen's Hall.

13:16.320 --> 13:18.277
Right, here's your keys.

13:18.480 --> 13:19.800
Thank you.

13:19.960 --> 13:22.190
Now, is there a bellboy?

13:26.040 --> 13:27.189
No-.

13:29.200 --> 13:30.190
All right.

13:30.360 --> 13:31.794
Most of you have realized

13:31.960 --> 13:34.190
it's been a wet and windy day
in Northern England,

13:34.360 --> 13:35.589
as it has been for quite some time...

13:35.760 --> 13:38.991
Oh, uh, my room in ten minutes?

13:39.560 --> 13:41.233
Your room in ten minutes?

13:41.400 --> 13:43.914
Yeah, we've gotta run those lines.

13:44.400 --> 13:45.435
Really?

13:45.600 --> 13:48.069
Sure, we're-we're almost done.

13:49.880 --> 13:52.872
All right. Yeah, I'll be right in.

14:09.080 --> 14:11.310
<i>What's the hotel like?</i>

14:11.480 --> 14:14.950
It's... like a castle.

14:15.160 --> 14:16.833
Well, that's wonderful.

14:17.040 --> 14:20.192
Everyone is so excited
about us touring again

14:20.360 --> 14:22.431
that we're being treated like kings.

14:22.600 --> 14:24.637
Well, Ida and I received our tickets today,

14:24.840 --> 14:26.911
so we're just as excited as can be.

14:27.080 --> 14:28.878
<i>Oh, and so am I.</i>

14:29.040 --> 14:32.999
So, how are things with Stanley?

14:33.160 --> 14:34.833
Well...

14:35.000 --> 14:36.752
you know Stan.

14:36.920 --> 14:39.639
Well, how has he been towards you?

14:39.800 --> 14:41.677
He... he's been good.

14:41.840 --> 14:44.719
It's... it's complicated.

14:44.880 --> 14:47.156
But we're just getting to know
each other again.

14:47.360 --> 14:49.397
It's... it's good.

14:49.560 --> 14:51.471
It's fine.

15:13.360 --> 15:14.509
<i>SCHENCK".
Are you sure Oliver</i>

15:14.720 --> 15:16.711
<i>wants to do this, Stan?</i>

15:22.520 --> 15:23.635
I mean,

15:23.800 --> 15:26.440
Fox would love to have you here, but...

15:28.200 --> 15:30.669
It's what we've both been waiting for, Joe.

15:30.840 --> 15:33.354
I-I can't understand
what's holding him up.

15:33.520 --> 15:37.718
He promised me he was finished
with Hal Roach Studios.

15:45.760 --> 15:47.592
Babe, where have you been?

15:47.800 --> 15:49.518
You had me worried for a minute there.

15:49.680 --> 15:51.034
Ha, ha. What the hell?

15:51.200 --> 15:53.555
You're here now. You're both here now.

15:56.600 --> 15:57.999
Here we are.

15:58.160 --> 16:00.231
Is this gonna be all right?

16:00.400 --> 16:02.994
It's just a movie, Babe.

16:04.400 --> 16:06.550
Mr. Hardy, when you touch her knee
with the mallet,

16:06.720 --> 16:08.757
she'll lift her leg
like you're checking her reflexes.

16:08.920 --> 16:10.433
All right. Thank you.

16:10.600 --> 16:12.113
Want to go for one, you two?

16:14.360 --> 16:16.271
Ready when you are, Ollie.

16:17.320 --> 16:18.958
Going to be great.

16:21.160 --> 16:22.480
Thank you, dear.

16:22.640 --> 16:24.711
You and Harry are
just gonna be great together.

16:27.400 --> 16:28.913
- Roll sound.
- Sound speed.

16:29.080 --> 16:30.639
- Roll camera.
- Camera speed.

16:30.840 --> 16:31.671
Mark it.

16:31.880 --> 16:33.279
"Zenobia," scene 21, take one.

16:34.680 --> 16:35.750
And... action!

16:36.880 --> 16:38.712
Why don't we have Stanley sign?

16:38.880 --> 16:39.836
Then all we have to do

16:40.000 --> 16:41.434
is have Oliver sign when he gets here.

16:41.640 --> 16:43.631
That's-that's a good idea,
right, Joe?

17:04.880 --> 17:06.154
Listen, we need to make sure

17:06.319 --> 17:09.358
we're in a nicer hotel
once the girls get here.

17:09.520 --> 17:11.113
Have you heard from Muffin?

17:11.280 --> 17:13.191
- Miffin.
- Miffin'?

17:13.359 --> 17:16.239
- Is that really his name?
- Mm-hm.

17:16.400 --> 17:18.516
Has he given you our shooting dates yet?

17:18.720 --> 17:20.313
I'm waiting on a call, Ollie.

17:20.480 --> 17:22.949
Hey, what do you think about this
as a title for the movie?

17:23.119 --> 17:24.758
- Hmm?
- "Rob 'Em Good."

17:24.920 --> 17:26.752
As a play on "Robin Hood."

17:26.920 --> 17:28.319
Right.

17:28.520 --> 17:30.352
Yeah, I like it.

17:30.520 --> 17:32.318
I-I've been working on this scene.

17:32.480 --> 17:34.630
Uh, uh, you and I

17:34.800 --> 17:37.030
break into the castle
to rescue Maid Marian.

17:37.240 --> 17:40.949
Right? And we're hiding
from the guards behind a curtain.

17:41.160 --> 17:43.674
Uh, uh, let me show you.

17:43.840 --> 17:46.992
Uh, you're the guard,
and, uh, uh, turn your head away.

17:47.160 --> 17:48.434
Ha-ha-ha. All right.

17:49.360 --> 17:51.078
Okay, so you grab a sword.

17:51.240 --> 17:53.550
Then you try and stab me
through the curtain.

17:53.720 --> 17:55.791
Hold on there. I have to get a sword.

17:55.960 --> 17:57.712
- You see that I'm hiding.
- Yes.

17:57.880 --> 18:00.394
You see by my feet I'm hiding,
so you stab at my head.

18:00.560 --> 18:02.278
Well, you can't hide from me.

18:04.520 --> 18:05.840
- Now what?
- And then you just

18:06.000 --> 18:07.752
grab the drapes
and pull them apart and...

18:13.240 --> 18:15.038
Is that funny?

18:18.400 --> 18:20.835
<i>Why you stay in guest house?</i>

18:21.000 --> 18:22.673
<i>You should be in best hotel.</i>

18:22.840 --> 18:24.672
Beggars can't be choosers, can they?

18:24.840 --> 18:27.275
<i>Okay, then why you not play West End?</i>

18:27.440 --> 18:29.636
No, no, no, no. I don't like this Delfont.

18:29.800 --> 18:32.235
Ida, he booked the tour for us, and we...

18:32.400 --> 18:35.597
we didn't exactly have
too many other offers, now, did we?

18:35.800 --> 18:38.792
And, anyway, we-we have
the movie to look forward to.

18:38.960 --> 18:41.076
<i>I guess the theater's a little small,
but that means</i>

18:41.240 --> 18:42.992
<i>- it'll be easier to sell out.
- Mm-hm, mm-hm.</i>

18:43.160 --> 18:45.993
How is Oliver? Hmm? He pulling weight?

18:46.160 --> 18:46.991
He's fine.

18:48.200 --> 18:49.076
Hello?

18:51.080 --> 18:52.832
Stanley!

18:53.000 --> 18:54.035
Hello.

18:54.200 --> 18:55.395
Hello? Ida?

18:55.560 --> 18:57.312
- Stanley.
- Thank goodness for that.

18:57.480 --> 18:59.517
<i>- Thought I 'd lost you.</i>
- Oy.

18:59.680 --> 19:01.717
Honey, I'm-I'm all out of change.
I gotta go.

19:01.880 --> 19:02.950
Okay, you hang up first.

19:03.160 --> 19:03.956
- No, no. You.
- Okay.

19:04.160 --> 19:05.958
On three. One. Two.

19:06.160 --> 19:07.992
<i>- Three. I love you!</i>
- I <i>love</i> you.

19:08.160 --> 19:09.514
Hello?

19:46.640 --> 19:47.960
Hello, Ollie.

19:48.160 --> 19:50.720
I didn't expect to see you here today.

19:50.880 --> 19:52.678
Well, I didn't have
anything better to do...

19:54.240 --> 19:56.038
...so I thought I'd come and see you.

19:57.120 --> 19:58.269
Thank you.

20:03.920 --> 20:05.115
What have you got there?

20:05.280 --> 20:08.352
I brought you some hard-boiled eggs
and some nuts.

20:09.440 --> 20:12.831
Now, you know
I can't eat hard-boiled eggs and nuts.

20:13.000 --> 20:14.877
If you wanted to bring me something,

20:15.040 --> 20:16.951
why didn't you bring me a box of candy?

20:17.120 --> 20:20.033
Well, you still haven't paid me
for the last box I brought you.

20:22.560 --> 20:25.951
Hard-boiled eggs and nuts.

20:26.160 --> 20:27.514
Mmm!

21:24.280 --> 21:27.989
What's going on out there
with all those empty seats?

21:30.400 --> 21:31.799
H-How's your knee?

21:31.960 --> 21:34.076
It hurts.

21:42.560 --> 21:45.313
Ladies and gentlemen,
thank you so very kindly.

21:45.480 --> 21:47.835
We hope you've enjoyed
our little bit of fun here tonight.

21:48.000 --> 21:49.638
We certainly have enjoyed ourselves.

21:49.800 --> 21:51.996
Pretty empty last night.

21:52.200 --> 21:54.111
Pretty empty?

21:54.280 --> 21:56.794
Could have invited
the entire audience back to our hotel,

21:57.000 --> 21:58.832
and there would have been
plenty of room.

21:59.040 --> 22:01.236
Listen, we have to make sure
Muffin doesn't come

22:01.400 --> 22:02.959
until these houses pick up.

22:03.120 --> 22:05.270
We don't want him getting cold feet
about the movie.

22:05.440 --> 22:08.239
Well, then I won't invite him
until we get to London.

22:08.400 --> 22:10.038
All right. You got it?

22:10.200 --> 22:12.999
- Yeah, I got it.
- Here.

22:13.160 --> 22:14.036
What time's our train?

22:15.360 --> 22:16.839
- 8:05.
- What time is it now?

22:17.000 --> 22:18.877
Hold this.

22:30.000 --> 22:32.674
Do we really need that trunk?

22:51.640 --> 22:55.110
How about I just punch you
right on the nose?

22:55.280 --> 22:57.669
I haven't done that for a long time.

22:57.840 --> 23:00.150
Can I poke you in the eye?

23:01.680 --> 23:03.034
You could wring my neck.

23:04.200 --> 23:05.873
I think I'd rather poke you in the eye.

23:06.040 --> 23:08.270
- It's simple.
- Yeah, but if you wring my neck,

23:08.440 --> 23:10.477
I can do that thing with my tongue.

23:15.280 --> 23:17.157
You know, I don't know if my knees

23:17.320 --> 23:19.834
- are gonna hold out for this.
- That's all right.

23:20.040 --> 23:22.270
We'll just finish with a song
instead of the dance.

23:22.440 --> 23:24.078
No, I don't mean the tour.

23:24.240 --> 23:27.119
I mean this scene in the movie
where I fall into the river.

23:27.280 --> 23:29.112
But that's historical, you-you know.
It's famous.

23:29.280 --> 23:31.078
Robin Hood has a fight
on the middle of the log.

23:31.240 --> 23:32.674
We-we gotta do that.

23:32.840 --> 23:35.958
It's a made-up story. Ha-ha.
It's not historical.

23:36.120 --> 23:39.954
All right, look, all I can say is
I'll do the best I can.

23:40.120 --> 23:42.555
Tell you what, I'll have a word
with the producer, Miffin.

23:42.720 --> 23:44.119
I'm sure he can cut round you

23:44.280 --> 23:47.033
when we...
when we shoot the picture.

23:47.440 --> 23:50.080
Maybe I will wring your neck.

23:50.920 --> 23:53.150
Mr. Miffin, please.

23:53.320 --> 23:55.197
It's Stan Laurel.

23:55.760 --> 23:57.956
L-A-U-R-E-L.

23:58.480 --> 24:00.312
That's right.

24:00.480 --> 24:03.279
Oh, that...
well, that's very kind of you to say.

24:04.640 --> 24:06.074
I'm afraid Mr. Hardy's, uh,

24:06.240 --> 24:08.311
indisposed right now.

24:08.480 --> 24:11.233
He's working in a Swiss cheese factory.

24:11.400 --> 24:13.994
He got the job putting the holes in.

24:15.920 --> 24:18.594
S-So, uh, Mr. Miffin?

24:19.840 --> 24:20.910
Is he? All right.

24:21.080 --> 24:23.549
Well, he-he sure does take
a lot of meetings.

24:23.720 --> 24:25.313
It's just that I need to confirm a date

24:25.520 --> 24:28.399
for him to come
and see our show in London.

24:30.400 --> 24:33.313
All right, no, well,
I'll-I'll call again another time.

24:33.480 --> 24:35.198
Thank you.

24:39.560 --> 24:42.712
- How's Ida?
- Oh, she's fine. You know.

24:42.880 --> 24:44.518
She says she's really looking forward

24:44.680 --> 24:46.478
to seeing you and Lucille again.

24:46.640 --> 24:48.472
- Very much.
- Good.

24:48.640 --> 24:51.154
Oh, I... I got you something.

24:51.320 --> 24:53.391
Oh.

24:53.560 --> 24:56.552
Here, hold onto this. Ha-ha.

24:59.560 --> 25:00.595
How do I look?

25:00.760 --> 25:02.034
- You look swell.
- Ha, ha.

25:03.040 --> 25:04.951
We're two peas in a pod.

25:05.120 --> 25:06.519
<i>We just want to know</i>

25:06.680 --> 25:08.637
who's playing Laurel and Hardy, please.

25:08.800 --> 25:11.030
- They're playing themselves.
- Who are?

25:11.200 --> 25:13.396
Laurel and Hardy, here in person.

25:13.560 --> 25:15.710
The poster says,
they're-they're here in person.

25:15.880 --> 25:17.473
But they've been retired for years.

25:17.640 --> 25:19.836
- They're playing themselves.
- Good afternoon, folks.

25:20.000 --> 25:21.399
- Look, Mammy.
- Hello.

25:21.560 --> 25:23.392
Oh, ma'am, I-if you're buying tickets,

25:23.560 --> 25:24.994
tell them you're friends of ours.

25:25.160 --> 25:26.559
He'll charge you extra.

25:27.640 --> 25:29.677
Two seats, front row.

25:29.880 --> 25:31.234
♪ Shine on ♪

25:31.400 --> 25:33.914
♪ Shine on, harvest moon ♪

25:34.080 --> 25:36.469
♪ Up in the sky ♪

25:36.680 --> 25:40.833
♪ I ain't had no loving
Since January ♪

25:41.000 --> 25:43.037
♪ April, June or July ♪

25:43.200 --> 25:46.272
♪ Snow time ain't no time ♪

25:46.480 --> 25:49.598
♪ To stay outdoors and spoon ♪

25:49.760 --> 25:52.229
♪ So shine on ♪

25:52.440 --> 25:55.034
♪ Shine on, harvest moon ♪

25:55.240 --> 25:57.197
♪ For me and my gal ♪♪

26:05.440 --> 26:08.637
Mmm. The eternal mysteries
of Scottish cuisine.

26:08.800 --> 26:10.950
- Hmm.
- Ever had haggis, Oliver?

26:11.120 --> 26:12.519
No-.

26:12.680 --> 26:14.353
Don't.

26:15.280 --> 26:18.671
Now, then, gentlemen,
can I just say, terrific show.

26:18.840 --> 26:19.989
Absolutely terrific.

26:20.160 --> 26:21.480
- Thank you. Yeah.
- Thank you.

26:21.680 --> 26:23.353
- I couldn't be happier.
- Well, let me tell you.

26:23.560 --> 26:25.233
We're going to be working
in some new material.

26:25.400 --> 26:26.674
- Right, Stan?
- Ooh.

26:26.840 --> 26:28.717
Yeah, we have a double-door routine,

26:28.880 --> 26:31.394
um, set in a railway station,
and when Babe's leg is better,

26:31.560 --> 26:32.959
we're going to reintroduce
the dance routine.

26:33.120 --> 26:34.838
Yes, and I think
that will all help enormously.

26:35.000 --> 26:37.560
Double-door routine...
audiences will love that.

26:37.720 --> 26:39.916
How do you feel about
the size of the audiences?

26:40.080 --> 26:42.993
To be honest,
I've been a little disappointed.

26:43.200 --> 26:44.520
And I think it's because of

26:44.680 --> 26:46.717
all these small theaters
we've been playing.

26:46.880 --> 26:49.110
Yes, and I am absolutely furious
about that.

26:49.280 --> 26:51.635
All due respect, Bernard,
you picked them.

26:51.800 --> 26:53.154
Now, I-l don't know what happened

26:53.320 --> 26:54.833
with the larger theaters
we were talking about...

26:55.000 --> 26:57.389
Well, they said they were all booked up.

26:57.560 --> 26:59.392
Yeah, by Norman Wisdom.

26:59.560 --> 27:01.790
Uh, isn't he one of your acts?

27:01.960 --> 27:04.315
Boys, the last thing I want to do
is start canceling shows.

27:04.480 --> 27:06.198
Wait, wait. Who's talking
about canceling shows?

27:06.360 --> 27:07.395
Not me.

27:07.600 --> 27:09.159
Well, we've only been at it a week.

27:09.320 --> 27:11.709
Yeah, wh-when do you plan
to finish this tour?

27:11.880 --> 27:14.110
Well, if we wrap things up
before we get to London,

27:14.280 --> 27:15.873
that would give us
another ten shows or so.

27:16.040 --> 27:17.838
And with a bit of a push, you know,

27:18.000 --> 27:19.399
final shows, that sort of thing,

27:19.560 --> 27:21.597
we should be able to go out with a bang.

27:21.760 --> 27:23.273
- In Hull.
- No. Wait, no.

27:23.440 --> 27:24.839
- Hull?
- We have this movie producer

27:25.000 --> 27:27.389
coming to our show
in London in a month.

27:27.560 --> 27:28.880
- Isn't that right, Stan?
- That's right.

27:29.080 --> 27:31.151
And Ida and Lucille, they're flying over.

27:31.320 --> 27:33.960
We can't finish
the show before London.

27:34.120 --> 27:35.952
- Bernard, we've been clear
- Mm-hm.

27:36.120 --> 27:37.918
That the only reason
we were doing this tour

27:38.080 --> 27:40.435
was so we could pull
that Robin Hood picture together.

27:40.600 --> 27:42.159
- That's right.
- Boys, boys, I know you're peeved,

27:42.320 --> 27:44.630
but could I just say, I am furious.

27:44.800 --> 27:46.393
I mean, they said,
"Oh, people don't come

27:46.600 --> 27:47.920
to the theater anymore."

27:48.080 --> 27:49.559
They said, "They just stay at home

27:49.720 --> 27:51.677
"watching their new television sets,
or they go

27:51.840 --> 27:52.955
"and watch Laurel and Hardy reruns

27:53.120 --> 27:54.679
- at the local picture house."
- We don't get paid

27:54.840 --> 27:56.672
- for those reruns, you know?
- That's what I said,

27:56.840 --> 27:58.194
and then they said, "Could you persuade

27:58.400 --> 27:59.913
"Stan and Ollie to do some publicity

28:00.080 --> 28:01.479
in order to turn the tour around?"

28:01.640 --> 28:03.677
Heh, heh. And I said, "lf you think

28:03.840 --> 28:05.274
"that I'm gonna ask Laurel and Hardy

28:05.440 --> 28:07.272
"to do some publicity stunts,
then you, my friend,

28:07.440 --> 28:09.670
are sorely mistaken."

28:11.680 --> 28:14.479
Hold on. Hold on, now.

28:15.120 --> 28:17.031
We could do that,
couldn't we, Stan?

28:17.200 --> 28:19.430
Sure, if you feel up to it, Babe.

28:19.600 --> 28:21.159
Sure.

28:21.320 --> 28:22.754
It would mean a very large amount

28:22.920 --> 28:24.399
of extra work for you both,

28:24.560 --> 28:26.119
making public appearances,
shop openings,

28:26.280 --> 28:28.476
meeting local dignitaries,
so on and so forth.

28:28.680 --> 28:31.194
- Would there be any more money?
- Ugh. They said no.

28:31.360 --> 28:32.873
Uh, who is "they"?

28:33.040 --> 28:35.156
People. The worst kind.

28:35.320 --> 28:37.391
Wait, I-I thought you were in charge.

28:37.560 --> 28:40.120
Ha-ha. So did I. Heh-heh-heh.

28:45.000 --> 28:47.116
- All right, we'll do it.
- Terrific.

28:47.280 --> 28:49.078
Well, I've told the press
and the newsreel boys

28:49.240 --> 28:51.470
that there'll be a welcoming committee
in Carlisle.

28:51.640 --> 28:53.472
Lord Mayor will be there.
He's desperate to see you.

28:53.640 --> 28:55.711
He is a huge fan.
I'll make some calls.

28:55.920 --> 28:57.638
Delicious.

29:02.960 --> 29:04.871
<i>Nothing new
about a couple of funnymen</i>

29:05.040 --> 29:06.269
<i>making personal appearances.</i>

29:06.440 --> 29:07.839
<i>But when Laurel and Hardy do it,</i>

29:08.000 --> 29:10.560
<i>you can expect complications.</i>

29:11.360 --> 29:13.271
<i>But even at a moment like this,</i>

29:13.480 --> 29:16.313
<i>trouble just seems to follow them around.</i>

30:13.720 --> 30:15.438
Oh!

30:15.600 --> 30:18.160
- What's the matter?
- My head hurts.

30:18.320 --> 30:20.072
I'll get a doctor.

30:20.240 --> 30:22.117
Oh!

30:22.280 --> 30:25.432
Never mind the doctor.
Just get my glass of water.

30:25.600 --> 30:26.431
Oh!

32:14.440 --> 32:15.999
Unbelievable.

32:16.200 --> 32:17.315
It certainly is.

32:28.320 --> 32:29.390
Sorry to bother you, chaps.

32:29.560 --> 32:32.029
Mr. Delfont would like to speak to you.

32:33.520 --> 32:34.840
Uh-oh.

32:35.000 --> 32:37.037
Any last words?

32:40.000 --> 32:41.798
Evening, gentlemen.

32:41.960 --> 32:43.792
If it's, uh, all right with you,

32:43.960 --> 32:45.997
I'd quite like to have
a discussion about...

32:46.160 --> 32:47.753
where we go from here.

32:47.920 --> 32:50.594
Let me guess. Back to America?

32:50.760 --> 32:52.478
Oblivion?

32:53.960 --> 32:56.190
That was...

32:56.560 --> 32:58.597
It was pure magic.

32:58.760 --> 32:59.795
It was brilliant.

32:59.960 --> 33:02.918
And ticket sales have improved
over the last week so much,

33:03.120 --> 33:05.760
mainly due to your efforts,

33:05.960 --> 33:07.792
we've sold out almost everywhere.

33:08.000 --> 33:09.149
Uh, what about London?

33:09.320 --> 33:11.436
Well, not only are we going to London,

33:11.600 --> 33:13.238
but so many people want
to come see the show

33:13.400 --> 33:15.311
that I've had to look for a bigger theater.

33:15.480 --> 33:18.279
So I've, uh... I've booked
the Lyceum for two weeks.

33:18.440 --> 33:20.238
We're guaranteed to sell it out.

33:20.400 --> 33:21.799
That's-that's over 2,000 seats.

33:21.960 --> 33:23.871
- Indeed.
- Heh, heh. Wow.

33:24.040 --> 33:25.269
Do you know, it's moments like this

33:25.480 --> 33:26.800
that make me love this industry.

33:26.960 --> 33:28.030
Madness.

33:28.200 --> 33:30.396
It's beautiful madness. Heh.

33:30.560 --> 33:34.030
And it's not about the money.
It is not about the money.

33:34.240 --> 33:35.310
I swear on...

33:35.480 --> 33:36.879
Well, I swear on both your lives.

33:37.040 --> 33:38.713
Ahem. You both feeling all right'?

33:42.560 --> 33:44.597
That's... that's pretty good, yeah.

33:44.760 --> 33:46.831
- Yeah, leave the jokes to us.
- All right.

33:48.520 --> 33:51.558
Seriously, though,
it's a very special evening.

33:51.720 --> 33:54.838
- Thank you, Bernie.
- Thank you.

34:00.520 --> 34:02.591
Well, that went well.

34:02.760 --> 34:04.194
It certainly did.

34:15.400 --> 34:18.313
So, you're on the log with Robin Hood,

34:18.480 --> 34:20.790
and he asks you what you want
to see him about,

34:20.960 --> 34:22.280
and then you say...

34:22.440 --> 34:24.750
"We're going to give him
a piece of my mind."

34:24.920 --> 34:26.114
"We certainly are."

34:26.280 --> 34:28.112
"We'd give him a piece of his, too,

34:28.280 --> 34:29.918
but he doesn't have any to spare."

34:30.080 --> 34:32.674
Heh, heh. Yeah, that's a nice line.

34:33.440 --> 34:36.114
Have you reached this Muffin fella yet?

34:37.480 --> 34:39.551
I mean,
I'm enjoying how the show's going,

34:39.760 --> 34:42.400
but it's the movie we're doing it for,
isn't it?

34:42.600 --> 34:43.829
Well, that's right, the...

34:44.000 --> 34:46.639
you know, one thing leads to another.

34:46.800 --> 34:48.552
Well, I sure hope so. Heh.

34:48.719 --> 34:51.838
Not exactly spring chickens anymore,
are we?

34:53.000 --> 34:56.197
London terminus, next and final stop.

34:56.400 --> 34:58.391
All change.

34:59.080 --> 35:01.515
Well, here we are.

35:01.680 --> 35:04.513
There it is, the Eiffel Tower.

35:48.560 --> 35:51.029
Ah, here we are.

35:51.800 --> 35:53.029
That's the one.

35:53.200 --> 35:54.634
- Look at that. That's wonderful.
- Yeah.

35:54.800 --> 35:56.837
- It's-it's a beautiful piece, sir.
- Hmm.

35:58.200 --> 35:59.634
Mr. Laurel not with you today?

35:59.840 --> 36:03.196
Oh, no, he got himself
a new job mending broken biscuits.

36:05.240 --> 36:07.754
I think it's wonderful you're still going.

36:08.600 --> 36:10.557
Well, rigor mortis has not set in yet.

36:18.720 --> 36:20.358
Sir, he's ready to see you now.

36:20.520 --> 36:23.239
- If you'd like to come along with me...
- Thank you.

36:24.760 --> 36:26.717
Good morning.

36:26.880 --> 36:28.837
Uh, I'm here to see Mr. Miffin.

36:29.040 --> 36:32.317
- And your name, please?
- Uh, Mr. Laurel.

36:33.160 --> 36:35.356
Do you have an appointment,
Mr. Lauren?

36:35.520 --> 36:38.433
Well, no, we keep missing
each other on the telephone,

36:38.600 --> 36:41.069
so I thought if I dropped by,
that'd be the easiest thing.

36:41.240 --> 36:43.151
'Cause he's not here right now.

36:44.800 --> 36:47.155
Well, I can wait.

36:51.080 --> 36:52.957
I think I-I've been speaking
to a different girl on...

36:53.120 --> 36:54.679
on the telephone about this.

36:54.840 --> 36:57.354
Uh, I've been speaking to her
for quite some time.

36:57.520 --> 36:59.511
She's left.

37:00.760 --> 37:02.717
Has she?

37:03.520 --> 37:06.876
You sure you want to wait?
He might be quite a while.

37:08.920 --> 37:11.719
Well, I'm here now, aren't I?

37:11.880 --> 37:13.951
Take a seat over there, Mr. Lauren.

37:14.120 --> 37:17.795
- Laurel. <i>- I'll</i>
let his office know that you're here.

37:26.040 --> 37:29.237
There's a gentleman here
says his name's Mr. Lauren.

37:32.240 --> 37:33.958
Right.

37:39.800 --> 37:43.156
You know,
now that I see these two together,

37:43.360 --> 37:44.759
I-I almost prefer this one.

37:44.920 --> 37:47.070
It's our finest bracelet.

37:47.280 --> 37:49.669
My wife is coming in from America today.

37:49.840 --> 37:51.638
It'll be a gift for her.

37:51.800 --> 37:54.110
- 350 pounds.
- Oh.

37:55.240 --> 37:57.914
Let me just double-check something
real quick here.

37:58.080 --> 38:01.994
Uh... do-do-do-do-da.

38:02.520 --> 38:04.750
Ah, yes.

38:05.320 --> 38:07.550
I wonder if you could hold
onto this for me.

38:07.760 --> 38:10.673
I-I seem to have brought
the wrong wallet with me.

38:10.840 --> 38:12.990
So I'll just tootle back to the hotel

38:13.160 --> 38:14.992
and be right back tout de suite.

38:15.160 --> 38:16.275
Of course, sir.

38:55.240 --> 38:56.310
<i>Hello, Raymond?</i>

38:56.520 --> 38:58.875
Well, I was wondering
if you could speak to your man

38:59.040 --> 39:01.077
and-and... and place a bet for me.

39:01.240 --> 39:02.753
Well, I'll tell you.

39:02.920 --> 39:07.391
It's Hometown Boy at Kempton,
the 2:30, five to one.

39:08.480 --> 39:09.959
Um...

39:10.120 --> 39:12.316
let-let's make it 60.

39:12.480 --> 39:14.118
60 pounds on the nose.

39:27.800 --> 39:29.996
Hello? Can I help you?

39:30.160 --> 39:32.151
Sorry. I have asked you to wait.

39:32.320 --> 39:33.879
Please, you're not allowed in there!

39:34.040 --> 39:35.758
Miss Clarke!

39:35.920 --> 39:38.673
Mr. Lauren's in Mr. Miffin's office!

39:42.040 --> 39:43.758
You're here to see Mr. Miffin?

39:43.920 --> 39:46.309
Yes, uh, I'm sorry, uh...

39:46.480 --> 39:47.675
uh, yes, I am.

39:47.840 --> 39:50.753
I'm his production executive,
Cynthia Clarke.

39:50.920 --> 39:53.480
- Hello, Cynthia.
- Oh.

39:54.040 --> 39:55.951
Mr. Miffin is still detained,

39:56.160 --> 39:57.958
but I've just spoken to him
on the telephone,

39:58.160 --> 40:00.515
and he wanted me
to explain the situation to you.

40:01.760 --> 40:04.036
He says he's sorry,
but he's been unable

40:04.200 --> 40:08.114
to raise the finance needed
to proceed with the film.

40:10.600 --> 40:12.591
Oh, I-l see.

40:12.800 --> 40:15.872
He said he made it clear
in a cable he sent to you

40:16.040 --> 40:17.633
before you left the United States

40:17.800 --> 40:21.316
that all the finance wasn't in place.

40:22.080 --> 40:26.392
Yes, well, I thought
he'd have it all lined up by now.

40:27.000 --> 40:29.435
He wanted you to know
that he did everything he could

40:29.600 --> 40:31.318
to bring the project together,

40:31.480 --> 40:33.118
but he feels sure you'll understand

40:33.320 --> 40:35.436
that the market is very challenging
at the moment

40:35.600 --> 40:38.399
and it simply wasn't possible.

40:41.240 --> 40:43.993
Yes, well... thank you.

40:44.160 --> 40:46.436
Uh, thank you for your time.

41:17.360 --> 41:19.954
<i>Get The Sporting Times.</i>

41:21.960 --> 41:23.473
<i>The Sporting Times, please.</i>

41:23.640 --> 41:25.677
There you are. Thank you.

41:26.200 --> 41:28.919
Get "The Sporting Times."

41:47.960 --> 41:51.510
- Bye-bye, now, kids.
- Bye-bye.

42:02.400 --> 42:04.630
- Oh, what's all this here?
- Oh.

42:04.800 --> 42:06.359
- All right, gents.
- Hi, boys.

42:06.520 --> 42:08.397
- Good afternoon, Mr. Hardy.
- Delfont's idea.

42:08.560 --> 42:10.039
He... he thought that the girls arriving

42:10.200 --> 42:12.271
would be a good excuse
for some free publicity.

42:12.440 --> 42:13.475
Ah.

42:13.640 --> 42:15.950
Hmm. I'm really looking forward
to seeing them.

42:16.120 --> 42:18.396
Oh, I've been counting the days.

42:18.560 --> 42:21.359
46. Since we got here.

42:21.520 --> 42:22.840
46 days.

42:23.000 --> 42:24.559
46? Heh, heh.

42:24.720 --> 42:26.757
Who counts from 46?

42:26.920 --> 42:28.149
I was missing her.

42:28.320 --> 42:29.958
Hey, I've been thinking.

42:30.120 --> 42:31.758
We don't need to tell the girls

42:31.920 --> 42:33.319
about everything
we've been doing, do we?

42:33.480 --> 42:34.914
- Um, no.
- I don't want to mention

42:35.080 --> 42:36.957
these personal appearances
and the drinking.

42:37.120 --> 42:39.634
Uh, no, th-there's no sense
in getting them all worked up.

42:39.800 --> 42:43.509
We'll just talk about how well
the tour's going and the movie.

42:44.520 --> 42:45.874
Sure, and the movie.

42:47.480 --> 42:48.709
Hey, if the car pulls up here,

42:48.920 --> 42:50.877
do you think
we could do the door routine?

42:51.040 --> 42:53.509
Heh. You just never stop, do you?

42:53.680 --> 42:55.830
- Ooh, here they are.
- Here they are. Okay.

42:56.000 --> 42:58.196
There she is. Oh...

43:02.040 --> 43:03.633
- Hey, sweetie pie.
- Hello.

43:03.800 --> 43:05.120
Hi, Stan.

43:05.280 --> 43:06.918
Hey, girls, will you
both get out this side?

43:07.080 --> 43:08.514
I've got something I want you to do.

43:08.680 --> 43:10.159
Of course, darling.
I give them my good side.

43:10.320 --> 43:11.674
Oh, no, Stanley, we just got here.

43:11.840 --> 43:13.194
- Come on, girls.
- Oh...

43:13.400 --> 43:15.152
<i>Comedy duo Laurel and Hardy</i>

43:15.360 --> 43:18.512
<i>were joined in London this week
by their wives.</i>

43:18.680 --> 43:20.910
<i>But even in a simple situation like this,</i>

43:21.080 --> 43:24.516
<i>trouble has a habit
of following them around.</i>

43:24.680 --> 43:26.353
<i>Oliver Hardy, Bachelor of Arts,</i>

43:26.520 --> 43:29.751
<i>always seems to have things
under control.</i>

43:30.360 --> 43:34.240
<i>But somehow,
things never quite work out that way.</i>

43:35.520 --> 43:37.477
<i>Yes, they're reunited again,</i>

43:37.640 --> 43:41.838
<i>and now everyone can start
making up for lost time.</i>

43:45.840 --> 43:47.194
Well, I hope they got all that.

43:47.360 --> 43:48.794
It's fine. It'll get a laugh.

43:48.960 --> 43:50.951
Oh, well, I'm awfully glad
about that, boys,

43:51.120 --> 43:53.509
but it would have been nice
to say hello to my husband

43:53.680 --> 43:55.830
without immediately being pressed
into one of your skits.

43:56.000 --> 43:57.798
Oh, Lord. It was just small fun.

43:57.960 --> 43:59.598
Oh, is that what it was, Ida?

43:59.760 --> 44:01.831
Don't be cross, angel.

44:02.000 --> 44:03.832
Who knows?
Maybe you'll get discovered.

44:04.000 --> 44:06.514
They could say,
"She ought to be in pictures."

44:06.680 --> 44:08.159
Heh. No. No, no, no, I don't...

44:08.320 --> 44:10.197
I don't think so, no.

44:12.080 --> 44:13.912
Oliver, can we visit the Tower of London

44:14.080 --> 44:15.150
and Saint Paul's?

44:15.320 --> 44:16.515
- Oh, and Harrods?
- Of course.

44:16.680 --> 44:18.034
Oh, and Buckingham Palace,

44:18.200 --> 44:20.350
where that darling new queen lives.

44:20.520 --> 44:22.796
Of course, angel.
You can visit anywhere you like.

44:22.960 --> 44:24.792
No, no, no,
Winter Palace in Saint Petersburg.

44:24.960 --> 44:26.439
- Oh, this is palace.
- Mm-hm.

44:26.640 --> 44:28.995
The Buckingham is little doghouse.

44:29.160 --> 44:30.878
We have been

44:31.040 --> 44:32.633
counting the days until you got here.

44:32.800 --> 44:34.632
- Oh.
- All 46 of them.

44:34.800 --> 44:37.235
- Did you know it was 46, Stan?
- Heh.

44:37.440 --> 44:39.875
How's the movie coming along, Stanley?

44:41.120 --> 44:42.633
Oh, it's, uh... it's all set up

44:42.800 --> 44:44.552
- for when we finish the tour.
- Oh.

44:44.720 --> 44:46.757
There's this producer fella named Muffin.

44:46.920 --> 44:47.955
Miffin.

44:48.160 --> 44:50.470
And, uh, Stan has rewritten his script.

44:50.640 --> 44:52.392
Oliver, that's enough salt.

44:52.560 --> 44:53.789
You know it's bad
for your blood pressure.

44:54.000 --> 44:55.798
Oh, sorry, angel, just a force of habit.

44:56.000 --> 44:57.479
Anyway, this producer is set to come by

44:57.640 --> 44:59.313
and see the show sometime next week.

44:59.480 --> 45:00.834
Isn't that right, Stan?

45:02.440 --> 45:06.195
Yeah, he said he'd-he'd try
and get along. Mm.

45:06.360 --> 45:08.874
Stan has been
taking wonderful care of me

45:09.040 --> 45:12.351
and making sure
that Daddy takes all of his tablets.

45:12.560 --> 45:13.994
Has he been taking
the blue ones, Stanley?

45:14.160 --> 45:16.436
Blue ones? I... I've been
giving him green ones.

45:16.600 --> 45:19.114
Green? Oh, my goodness.
Oliver, what are they?

45:19.320 --> 45:20.640
- He's kidding.
- Heh, heh, heh.

45:20.800 --> 45:22.199
Well, I'm not finding that funny.

45:22.400 --> 45:24.676
- I was dancer. Yes?
- Oh.

45:24.840 --> 45:26.478
I dance for Preston Sturges.

45:26.640 --> 45:28.597
- I dance for Harold Lloyd.
- Really, Ida?

45:28.760 --> 45:30.114
You've never mentioned this before.

45:30.280 --> 45:32.840
When my knee hurt,
what I do, hmm?

45:33.040 --> 45:35.031
I dance some more, yes?

45:35.200 --> 45:38.591
I go faster, I jump high,
and hurt go away.

45:38.760 --> 45:40.592
- Oh. Mm.
- Hmm? I forget pain,

45:40.800 --> 45:43.314
because pain is only in your mind, Oliver.

45:43.480 --> 45:45.278
It's not in his mind, Ida.
It's in his knee.

45:45.440 --> 45:47.636
And there's no way that you can do
the scene in this movie

45:47.800 --> 45:49.199
where you fall into the river.

45:49.360 --> 45:51.636
- I've been telling her about the script.
- Oh.

45:51.800 --> 45:55.191
- Director can use double.
- That's what I told her.

45:55.360 --> 45:56.634
- Sturges use double.
- It's okay

45:56.800 --> 45:58.029
for Babe to sit about in a river all day,

45:58.200 --> 45:59.270
is it, catching his death of cold?

45:59.480 --> 46:00.515
Honestly, Stanley, come on.

46:00.680 --> 46:02.239
Why you say Stanley?

46:02.440 --> 46:03.714
- What?
- What?

46:03.880 --> 46:06.599
Anyway, show must go on, yes?

46:06.760 --> 46:07.875
And don't worry about river jump.

46:08.040 --> 46:09.758
It's easy as cake.

46:09.920 --> 46:12.196
- Easy as pie.
- Yeah, it's-it's a piece of cake.

46:12.360 --> 46:14.237
That's what I say.

46:16.320 --> 46:18.834
What do you see
in a fat old man like me'?

46:19.040 --> 46:22.999
Hey, you, that's my husband
you're talking about.

46:24.320 --> 46:28.200
I love you, and you can't stop me.

46:29.720 --> 46:32.075
- Well, all right.
- Mmm.

46:38.040 --> 46:39.917
How was the trip over with Ida?

46:40.080 --> 46:42.356
Oh, you know Ida. Exhausting.

46:42.520 --> 46:44.431
When she gets something in her head,

46:44.600 --> 46:47.513
she won't let it go
till she's worried it to death,

46:47.680 --> 46:49.398
and God forbid anyone should raise

46:49.560 --> 46:51.278
the slightest criticism of Stanley.

46:51.440 --> 46:53.272
Heh, heh. She's a real piece of work.

46:53.440 --> 46:55.078
Yeah.

46:55.920 --> 46:58.719
Has he been pushing you
a little too hard, Babe?

46:58.880 --> 47:00.518
No-.

47:02.520 --> 47:04.591
I mean, it is a bit more difficult

47:04.800 --> 47:08.350
than I thought it might be, but...

47:09.560 --> 47:11.915
the show must go on.

47:18.400 --> 47:22.109
I think she wear pants
in Hardy house, no?

47:22.280 --> 47:26.114
Oliver is like cat
on hot roof with Lucille.

47:26.320 --> 47:27.879
Babe's been like that with all his wives.

47:28.040 --> 47:29.360
He runs round after them,

47:29.520 --> 47:31.193
jumping up and down,
trying to please them.

47:31.360 --> 47:32.873
Oh, you can learn this?

47:34.240 --> 47:36.038
She's been good for him,

47:36.200 --> 47:38.430
considering the state he was in.

47:38.600 --> 47:40.796
The state we were both in.

47:44.120 --> 47:46.396
But now we don't drink
and we don't smoke,

47:46.560 --> 47:49.154
and we're very happy-

47:49.800 --> 47:52.952
He should say thank you to you
for all you do for him.

47:53.120 --> 47:56.909
You could have long time ago said,
"Goodbye, Oliver."

47:57.080 --> 48:01.153
That's all in the past,
and it's where it should stay.

48:02.280 --> 48:04.032
Thank you.

48:04.440 --> 48:05.919
You crazy. Send it back.

48:06.080 --> 48:07.673
I don't want to drink it.
I just want to smell it.

48:07.840 --> 48:09.160
No, it's bad for diabetes.

48:09.360 --> 48:10.839
No-.

48:13.880 --> 48:15.791
Now you can't drink.

48:22.360 --> 48:25.318
I don't want to lose you, Stanley.

48:34.040 --> 48:35.713
Mmm.

48:36.920 --> 48:40.675
And to think nobody knows
that you're really a man.

49:03.960 --> 49:06.634
Would you like me to arrange
you tickets for Norman Wisdom?

49:06.800 --> 49:08.154
Oh, I don't know who that is.

49:08.320 --> 49:10.072
Oh, one of the comic minds
of our generation.

49:10.240 --> 49:11.469
Oh, well, that's wonderful.

49:11.640 --> 49:12.869
<i>- I'll</i> speak to Oliver.
- Absolutely.

49:13.040 --> 49:14.519
- Yea high, cap. After you.
- Thank you. Oh.

49:14.720 --> 49:15.994
- Mm-mm. No, no, no. No, no.
- What?

49:16.160 --> 49:17.673
No, I don't want to sit next to him.

49:17.840 --> 49:18.989
- Hello. Hello.
- Evening.

49:19.880 --> 49:22.156
Sold out. Wonderful.

49:22.320 --> 49:23.833
Huge box office.

49:24.000 --> 49:26.389
- Who?
- They sold a lot of tickets, Ida.

